a Vie, I don't think I've ever come across an SK or Necro that wasn't fanatically serving Innoruuk. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bpaladinsofnorrath.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=callalily>Callalily</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Noble Squire</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/9/02 1:04:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgodsmightroleplaytavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=117.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re:  A DIFFERENT way to roleplay a paladin</span><hr size=1> I must say, I've played D&amp;D for about 10 years. It gets tiring seeing the people who go to either extreme and call it role-playing. The problem is you get people on one side who develop a story where there is little internal conflict. They are paladin. They are Lawful Good. They do wield a holy weapon. And they do destroy evil. And then you get the people who try just a little too hard. They are NOT lawful good anymore(Yet they want to be a paladin. And some DM's let them.), they learn from evil, and their holy weapons helps them to kill innocents if they get in the way. Now, the problem is that I don't really like these extremes. However, both are valid. Both deserve recognition. And both can have interesting stories. A God, for instance, may choose to continue to give power to a fallen paladin if his actions have the possibility to cause a greater good.<br><br>For instance, I have a friend(how many stories start like this). I was playing a cleric of a particular faith and he was playing a paladin of that same faith. It comes to the surface that there are some very corrupt(supernaturally so) characters within our group. My friend, at first, does not lose faith in the God, but lost faith in it's practice. Meanwhile, my character is advancing and learning of the inner workings of the church and why some of the head of the church are corrupt as such. Our characters are very often at odds, even though he has sworn to be my procterate knight.<br><br>He eventually does fall, and takes up an oath to destroy the church. With the oath, came new responsibilities and new powers as the very high end encounters in the church are vampiric in nature. However, his new patriarch's abilities are unknown. He was blinded, because of hatred and THAT is what made him fall.<br><br>It is quite a bit more interesting to play characters that are at least slightly left of center. Those are the characters we most love in books. The best characters have some internal conflict. The first poster might, for instance, see the power that this necromancer wielded. Finding some disgust in the way his people worship he would like to return them to the faith. With power like the necromancer had, maybe it would be attainable. Maybe if he could raise the dead for instance, he could have them speak of their afterlife. To put the fright of disobeying Tunare in them. Maybe he feels, internally, that he is getting nowhere in his fights against evil. He knew very little about them and now that he knows and cares for his enemy he will be a greater service to tunare. At some point he might snap out of it, maybe even bring a child of Innoruk back to the Tunare where he should be now if Innoruk had not twisted his people.<br><br>The point I'm trying to make is that there are fine lines that one can validly walk. Building that bit of the story is what makes them much more of a hero. Because they were once weak we as people can identify with them. Because everything isn't black or white we as people can identify with them. Anyway, that's just my opinion. The important thing about RPing is that ya have fun doing it.<br> <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=158863">Callalily Serein</A><BR>The Littlest Knight of Karana<BR></p><i></i></td>