rusader Wars. <br><br>Though the popular belief of paladins is the romantic notion they are beyond evil, this is not the case in history. Rather the church forgave the crusaders their sins in exchange for service to the church. To kill another human being is considered a cardinal sin in most religions and belief structures. Yet the crusaders (and their like) not only entered war with the intent to kill but to carry that war into the homeland of the non-believers to slay any who would not accept their god. Many history documents refer to the rape, pillage (act of theft), and plunder (loot) committed during the crusades. Not to mention the slaughter of innocents if the believed in a “false” god. <br><br>I conclude that in the role-play of a paladin, it is not the fearless, righteous, and good-hearted icon that so many seem to believe. Rather, a warrior that believes any sin he does in the name of the church is forgiven in service of the church. That the act of carrying his deity’s will on earth makes any sin a small price in the “big-picture” of an eternal struggle of the god. The only difference (other than game mechanics) in the role-play of a Anti-Paladin or Shadow Knight that accepts damnation is that a Paladin believes the forgiveness of sin in the name of the church places them beyond sin. <br><br>Below are some references to consider before flaming. Afterward, flame on ~ we are all entitled to our opinions. <br><br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.starpoint.wnyric.org/inter/leible/holywars.htm">www.starpoint.wnyric.org/...lywars.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>The Crusades may have been seen as &quot;holy&quot; wars, but they brought lasting terror and misery to the Near East.  There were eight major Crusades from 1096 to 1270.<br><br><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.templarhistory.com/worms.htm">www.templarhistory.com/worms.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>Massacre at Worms of hundreds of innocent people by th